  "Only analyzing the financial stakes of environmental cleanup": "",
  "Only identifying the government agencies responsible for enforcement": "",
  "Identifying all affected parties including industry, communities, environmental groups, and government agencies, and analyzing their interests and influence": "",
  "Stakeholder analysis systematically identifies all parties affected by or involved in an environmental policy, examines their interests, concerns, and relative influence, and considers how the policy will affect each group differently.": "",
  "What is the difference between point-source and non-point source pollution in terms of regulation?": "",
  "Non-point source pollution is easier to regulate because it affects larger areas": "",
  "Point-source pollution is easier to regulate because it comes from identifiable discharge points that can be monitored and permitted": "",
  "There is no regulatory difference between the two types": "",
  "Point-source pollution is more dangerous and therefore harder to regulate": "",
  "Point-source pollution from identifiable discharge points (pipes, smokestacks) can be directly monitored and regulated through permits, while non-point source pollution from diffuse origins (agricultural runoff, urban stormwater) is much harder to track and control.": "",
  "What is the role of voluntary environmental programs like Energy Star?": "",
  "They are completely useless and should be eliminated": "",
  "They are identical to mandatory regulations in their effectiveness": "",
  "They are sufficient on their own to solve environmental problems": "",
  "Useful supplements to mandatory regulation but insufficient alone, as they are typically only adopted by companies that benefit from compliance": "",
  "Voluntary programs can complement mandatory regulations by encouraging leadership and market differentiation, but they are insufficient alone because they tend to attract only participants who already benefit from compliance, leaving laggards unaffected.": "",
  "What is the concept of equity in environmental policy analysis?": "",
  "Ensuring all companies pay the exact same amount in compliance costs": "",
  "Only the total benefits of a policy matter, not who receives them": "",
  "Only the total cost of a policy matters, not who pays": "",
  "Examining who bears the costs and who receives the benefits of a policy to ensure it does not disproportionately burden vulnerable communities": "",
  "Equity analysis examines the distributional impacts of environmental policy, asking who bears the costs and who enjoys the benefits, to ensure that vulnerable communities are not disproportionately burdened.": "",
  "What is the 'race to the bottom' in environmental regulation?": "",
  "The competition among jurisdictions to have the weakest environmental standards in order to attract industry and investment": "",
  "The competition among agencies for the lowest enforcement budget": "",
  "The decline in public interest in environmental issues over time": "",
  "The rapid decline in water quality at the bottom of rivers": "",
  "The 'race to the bottom' occurs when jurisdictions competitively weaken their environmental standards to attract businesses and investment, potentially undermining environmental protection across all jurisdictions.": "",
  "What is the concept of ecosystem services in policy analysis?": "",
  "The cost of maintaining endangered species in captive breeding programs": "",
  "Services provided by environmental agencies to maintain ecosystems": "",
  "The fees charged by national parks for ecosystem access": "",
  "The benefits that humans derive from ecosystems, such as clean water, pollination, flood control, and climate regulation, which often have economic value not captured in markets": "",
  "Ecosystem services are the benefits nature provides to humans, including water purification, pollination, flood protection, and carbon sequestration, many of which have substantial economic value not reflected in market transactions.": "",
