  "A city has a severe traffic congestion and air pollution problem. The city council is debating between two proposals: Proposal A would ban vehicles that do not meet specific emission standards from the city center. Proposal B would implement a congestion pricing charge for all vehicles entering the center during peak hours. Which approach is command-and-control and which is market-based?": "",
  "Proposal A is command-and-control (specific vehicle emission standards) and Proposal B is market-based (pricing to influence behavior)": "",
  "Proposal A is market-based (pricing) and Proposal B is command-and-control (standards)": "",
  "Both are command-and-control approaches": "",
  "Both are market-based approaches": "",
  "Proposal A is command-and-control because it sets specific emission standards vehicles must meet. Proposal B is market-based because it uses a price signal (congestion charge) to influence driver behavior and reduce traffic.": "",
  "A factory releases pollutants into a river, causing health problems downstream. The cost of treating these health problems is $5 million per year, but the factory does not pay for this damage. Instead, downstream residents and their health insurers bear the costs. A policy analyst proposes a pollution tax to address this situation. In economic terms, what is the pollution creating and what would the tax accomplish?": "",
  "The pollution creates a positive externality, and the tax would increase production efficiency": "",
